"Rummukainen M., Räisänen J., Bjørge D., Christensen J.H., Christensen O.B., Iversen T., Jylhä K., Ólafsson H., Tuomenvirta H.","Regional climate scenarios for use in Nordic water resources studies",2003,"Nordic Hydrology","34","5",,"399","412",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-1442314051&partnerID=40&md5=e4269f1895996a18480c3cae33811064","Swedish Meteorol./Hydrological Inst., Norrköping SE-601 76, Sweden; Norwegian Meteorological Institute, P.O. Box 43, Blindern, Oslo N-0313, Norway; Danish Meteorological Institute, Lyngbyvej 100, Copenhagen Ø DK-2100, Denmark; Finnish Meteorological Institute, P.O. Box 503, Helsinki FIN-00101, Finland; Islandic Meteorological Organisation, Bústadavegur 9, Reykjavik IS-150, Iceland","Rummukainen, M., Swedish Meteorol./Hydrological Inst., Norrköping SE-601 76, Sweden; Räisänen, J., Swedish Meteorol./Hydrological Inst., Norrköping SE-601 76, Sweden; Bjørge, D., Norwegian Meteorological Institute, P.O. Box 43, Blindern, Oslo N-0313, Norway; Christensen, J.H., Danish Meteorological Institute, Lyngbyvej 100, Copenhagen Ø DK-2100, Denmark; Christensen, O.B., Danish Meteorological Institute, Lyngbyvej 100, Copenhagen Ø DK-2100, Denmark; Iversen, T., Norwegian Meteorological Institute, P.O. Box 43, Blindern, Oslo N-0313, Norway; Jylhä, K., Finnish Meteorological Institute, P.O. Box 503, Helsinki FIN-00101, Finland; Ólafsson, H., Islandic Meteorological Organisation, Bústadavegur 9, Reykjavik IS-150, Iceland; Tuomenvirta, H., Finnish Meteorological Institute, P.O. Box 503, Helsinki FIN-00101, Finland","According to global climate projections, a substantial global climate change will occur during the next decades, under the assumption of continuous anthropogenic climate forcing. Global models, although fundamental in simulating the response of the climate system to anthropogenic forcing are typically geographically too coarse to well represent many regional or local features. In the Nordic region, climate studies are conducted in each of the Nordic countries to prepare regional climate projections with more detail than in global ones. Results so far indicate larger temperature changes in the Nordic region than in the global mean, regional increases and decreases in net precipitation, longer growing season, shorter snow season etc. These in turn affect runoff, snowpack, groundwater, soil frost and moisture, and thus hydropower production potential, flooding risks etc. Regional climate models do not yet fully incorporate hydrology. Water resources studies are carried out off-line using hydrological models. This requires archived meteorological output from climate models. This paper discusses Nordic regional climate scenarios for use in regional water resources studies. Potential end-users of water resources scenarios are the hydropower industry, dam safety instances and planners of other lasting infrastructure exposed to precipitation, river flows and flooding.",,"Computer simulation; Floods; Groundwater; Hydroelectric power; Hydrology; Moisture; Snow; Soils; Water resources; Anthropogenic climate forcing; Climate change; climate change; climate effect; hydrological cycle; regional climate; water resource; Eurasia; Europe; Northern Europe; Scandinavia",,,,,,"Bergström, S., Carlsson, B., Gardelin, M., Lindström, G., Pettersson, A., Rummukainen, M., Climate change impacts on runoff in Sweden - Assessments by global climate models, dynamical downscaling and hydrological modelling (2001) Clim. Res., 16, pp. 101-112; Christensen, J.-H., Räisämen, J., Iversen, T., Bjørge, D., Christensen, O.B., Rummukainen, M., A synthesis of regional climate change simulations. A Scandinavian perspective (2001) Geophys. Res. Lett., 28, pp. 1003-1006; Graham, L.P., Rummukainen, M., Gardelin, M., Bergström, S., Modelling climate change impacts on water resources in the Swedish regional climate modelling programme (2001) Detecting and Modelling Regional Climate Change and Associated Impacts, pp. 567-580. , M. Brunet and D. López (Editors), Springer-Verlag, Berlin/Heidelberg/New York; (2001) Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis. Contribution of Working Group I to the Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, p. 881. , IPCC [Houghton, J. T., Ding, Y., Griggs, D. J., Noguer, M., van der Linden, P. J., Dai, X., Maskell, K., and Johnson, C. A. (eds.)]. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, United Kingdom and New York, NY, USA; Knutti, R., Stocker, T.F., Joos, F., Plattner, G.-K., Constraints on radiative forcing and future climate change from observations and climate model ensembles (2002) Nature, 416, pp. 719-723; Krishnamurti, T.N., Kishtawal, C.M., LaRow, T.E., Bachiochi, D.R., Zhang, Z., Williford, C.E., Gadgil, S., Surendran, S., Improved weather and seasonal climate forecasts from multimodel superensemble (1999) Science, 285, pp. 1548-1550; Mitchell, J.F.B., Johns, T.C., Eagles, M., Ingram, W.J., Davis, R.A., Towards the construction of climate change scenarios (1999) Clim. Change, 41, pp. 547-581; Räisänen, J., CO2-induced climate change in CMIP2 experiments. Quantification of agreement and role of internal variability (2001) J. of Climate, 14, pp. 2088-2104; Räisänen, J., Joelsson, R., Changes in average and extreme precipitation in two regional climate model experiments (2001) Tellus, 53 A, pp. 547-566; Stott, P., Kettleborough, J.A., Origins and estimates of uncertainty in predictions of twenty-first century temperature rise (2002) Nature, 416, pp. 723-726; Sælthun, N.R., Aittoniemi, P., Bergström, S., Einarsson, K., Jóhannesson, T., Lindström, G., Ohlsson, P.-E., Aamodt, K.O., Climate change impacts on runoff and hydropower in the Nordic countries (1998) TemaNord, 1998 (552), p. 170; Zwiers, F.W., The 20-year forecast (2002) Nature, 416, pp. 690-691","Rummukainen, M.; Swedish Meteorol./Hydrological Inst., Norrköping SE-601 76, Sweden; email: Markku.Rummukainen@smhi.se",,,,,,,,00291277,,,,"English","Nord. Hydrol.",Article,Scop